00:02:09,946 --> 00:02:11,860
And it's rather important

36
00:02:11,860 --> 00:02:15,920
because I had done 15 years of research before it,

37
00:02:15,920 --> 00:02:18,348
so I had a backlog, so it was easy.

38
00:02:18,348 --> 00:02:20,108
It's not that I was Fidel Castro

39
00:02:20,108 --> 00:02:21,941
and I could talk for two hours,

40
00:02:21,941 --> 00:02:23,263
or Bucky Fuller.

41
00:02:23,263 --> 00:02:25,178
I had 15 years of stuff,

42
00:02:25,178 --> 00:02:27,650
and the Media Lab was about to start.

43
00:02:27,650 --> 00:02:29,450
So that was easy.

44
00:02:29,450 --> 00:02:32,114
But there are a couple of things

45
00:02:32,114 --> 00:02:33,802
about that period

46
00:02:33,802 --> 00:02:35,855
and about what happened that are

47
00:02:35,855 --> 00:02:37,710
really quite important.

48
00:02:37,710 --> 00:02:40,266
One is that

49
00:02:40,266 --> 00:02:43,162
it was a period when computers

50
00:02:43,162 --> 00:02:45,799
weren't yet for people.

51
00:02:45,799 --> 00:02:48,944
And the other thing that sort of happened

52
00:02:48,944 --> 00:02:52,015
during that time is that

53
00:02:52,015 --> 00:02:55,397
we were considered sissy computer scientists.

54
00:02:55,397 --> 00:02:56,960
We weren't considered the real thing.

55
00:02:56,960 --> 00:03:00,959
So what I'm going to show you is, in retrospect,

56
00:03:00,959 --> 00:03:03,467
a lot more interesting and a lot more accepted

57
00:03:03,467 --> 00:03:05,533
than it was at the time.

58
00:03:05,533 --> 00:03:08,087
So I'm going to characterize the years

59
00:03:08,087 --> 00:03:09,920
and I'm even going to go back

60
00:03:09,920 --> 00:03:12,024
to some very early work of mine,

61
00:03:12,024 --> 00:03:14,910
and this was the kind of stuff I was doing in the '60s:

62
00:03:14,910 --> 00:03:17,097
very direct manipulation,

63
00:03:17,097 --> 00:03:19,752
very influenced as I studied architecture

64
00:03:19,752 --> 00:03:21,839
by the architect Moshe Safdie,

65
00:03:21,839 --> 00:03:24,601
and you can see that we even built robotic things

66
00:03:24,601 --> 00:03:27,357
that could build habitat-like structures.

67
00:03:27,357 --> 00:03:29,044
And this for me was

68
00:03:29,044 --> 00:03:30,960
not yet the Media Lab,

69
00:03:30,960 --> 00:03:33,777
but was the beginning of what I'll call

70
00:03:33,777 --> 00:03:35,296
sensory computing,

71
00:03:35,296 --> 00:03:37,168
and I pick fingers

72
00:03:37,168 --> 00:03:41,370
partly because everybody thought it was ridiculous.

73
00:03:41,370 --> 00:03:43,525
Papers were published

74
00:03:43,525 --> 00:03:47,777
about how stupid it was to use fingers.

75
00:03:47,777 --> 00:03:50,595
Three reasons: One was they were low-resolution.

76
00:03:50,595 --> 00:03:52,524
The other is your hand would occlude

77
00:03:52,524 --> 00:03:53,965
what you wanted to see,

78
00:03:53,965 --> 00:03:55,723
and the third, which was the winner,

79
00:03:55,723 --> 00:03:59,379
was that your fingers would get the screen dirty,

80
00:03:59,379 --> 00:04:01,705
and hence, fingers would never be

81
00:04:01,705 --> 00:04:03,493
a device that you'd use.

82
00:04:03,493 --> 00:04:06,542
And this was a device we built in the '70s,

83
00:04:06,542 --> 00:04:08,413
which has never even been picked up.

84
00:04:08,413 --> 00:04:09,854
It's not just touch sensitive,

85
00:04:09,854 --> 00:04:12,032
it's pressure sensitive.

86
00:04:12,032 --> 00:04:14,009
